</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Danilov, 2017" authorityName="Danilov" authorityYear="2017" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="asiatica" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">P. asiatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[247,311,689,714]" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[247,311,689,714]" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in having the propodeal enclosure with erect setae, and the body erect setae predominantly black. It differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Tsuneki" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[295,431,725,749]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="altaiensis">
<emphasis box="[295,431,725,749]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">P. altaiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shape of the penis valve, which in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Tsuneki" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[916,1053,725,749]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="altaiensis">
<emphasis box="[916,1053,725,749]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">P. altaiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is slenderer and with only a very small transverse spines (which in 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Bohart &amp; Menke" authorityYear="1976" baseAuthorityName="Dalla Torre" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[532,699,762,785]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turcestanica">
<emphasis box="[532,699,762,785]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">P. turcestanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are well defined as in figs 108–110). It differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1763" box="[1293,1400,761,785]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsuta">
<emphasis box="[1293,1400,761,785]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">P. hirsuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shape of the penis valve, and in having the body with only black setae (in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1763" box="[1022,1126,797,821]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsuta">
<emphasis box="[1022,1126,797,821]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">P. hirsuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the penis valve is broader, and the mesosoma with the black and pale setae). It differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Dollfuss, 2010 b:" authorityYear="1249" box="[876,975,833,857]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andrei">
<emphasis box="[876,975,833,857]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">P. andrei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the body with only black setae and a less extended red color of the metasoma: T1–T2 red (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Dollfuss, 2010 b:" authorityYear="1249" box="[904,1009,869,893]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andrei">
<emphasis box="[904,1009,869,893]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">P. andrei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the metapleuron and the propodeal enclosure have pale setae, and T1–T4 are red). It differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kohl" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[840,981,905,929]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrohirta">
<emphasis box="[840,981,905,929]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">P. nigrohirta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Danilov, 2017" authorityName="Danilov" authorityYear="2017" box="[1035,1151,906,929]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="asiatica" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1035,1151,906,929]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">P. asiatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1157,1220,905,930]" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1157,1220,905,930]" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
by the shape of the penis valve (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Danilov" authorityYear="2017" box="[323,439,942,965]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="asiatica">
<emphasis box="[323,439,942,965]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">P. asiatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the penis valve is broader; in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kohl" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[782,924,941,965]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrohirta">
<emphasis box="[782,924,941,965]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="568">P. nigrohirta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with only very small transverse spines).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
